  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States and internationally:\n\n1. U.S. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandate record-keeping\n- Establish criminal penalties for money laundering\n- Impose reporting requirements for cash transactions over $10,000\n\n3. International Frameworks:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n\n4. Criminal Penalties:\n- Potential fines\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Imprisonment\n- Civil and criminal sanctions\n\n5. Enforcement Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation\n\nThese statutes are designed to detect, prevent, and prosecute financial crimes involving illegal money transfers and concealment of illicit funds.",
